  <h3>Arrays</h3>
  <p>Arrays contain ordered list of elements or objects. It can contain strings, integers, floats, etc...The index of an array starts with 0.
  <br></br> In other words, if you were to select an element from the array, the first element you see will be called using array[0].</p>
    <ul type="square">
    <li>Example 1</li><p>What if I want to retrieve 6 from the array?</p>
    <code>
      x = [1,2,3,4,5,6,7,2.0,5.9,9.9]<br>
      x[5]<br>
      =>6
    </code>
    <br></br>
    <li>Example 2</li><p>What if I want to retrieve the string "everyday"?</p>
    <code>
      z = ["Spike the good pupper", "likes to bark", "at the mailman", "everyday."]<br>
      z[3]<br>
      =>"everyday"
    </code>
    <br></br>
    <li>Example 3</li><p>How about iterating through each element?</p>
    <code>
      dogs = ["Spike", "Marco", "Lexi", "Kirby"]<br>
      dogs.each{|d| puts "Hello #{d}"}<br>
      Hello Spike<br>
      Hello Marco<br>
      Hello Lexi<br>
      Hello Kirby
    </code>
  </ul>
  <h3>Hashes</h3><p>Hashes contains key/ value pairs. It uses curly braces {} and a hash rocket =></p>
